      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks. so if you look at the actual phrasing, originalists argue that if the text says 'the right of the people to keep and bear arms shall not be infringed,' then any restriction is basically unconstitutional. does that make the originalist position more 'legally sound' compared to the living constitution view, which relies more on modern policy concerns?",
